  <span id="freeText8512368865967294450" style="display:none">After the success of Shi Nai An "Au bord de l'eau", it was the second Chinese novel to enter in the "Pléiade" collection. I was a little surprised. This is more the picaresque novel.It is almost a novel XIX° the rise and fall of the Jia House. <br />And there are also Romeo and Juliette. The rhythm is slow, one needs to accept it. I had evil to locate me geographically. I visited in China a long time after its reading the house of the merchant Wang who was the decor of "Wives and concubines."<br />I then understood how this closed world functioned, all seemingly. The novel appeared to me much more clearly.<br />It is necessary that I read again this book because I have the impression to be last with dimensions.</span>
