<div id="review_322867793" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/322867793" />
    <a title="Spencer Rich" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9226864-spencer-rich"><img alt="Spencer Rich" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581637117p2/9226864.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/322867793?book_show_action=true">May 02, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Spencer Rich" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Spencer Rich" href="/user/show/9226864-spencer-rich">Spencer Rich</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer322867793" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3314332739583120573">A good introduction to the novel. I was first introduced to this version via a World Lit class at the University of North Carolina--Wilmington. It had such a deep effect on me that I re-read it several times and eventually read the five volume version numerous times. I would say that the five-volume translation has become probably my favorite of all-time, perhaps, next to <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5129.Brave_New_World' title='Brave New World by Aldous Huxley' rel='nofollow noopener'>Brave New World</a>. It has all the genius of the Romantic-era novels of manners, e.g. <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1885.Pride_and_Prejudice' title='Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen' rel='nofollow noopener'>Pride and Prejudice</a> set against a backgrou</span>
  <span id="freeText3314332739583120573" style="display:none">A good introduction to the novel. I was first introduced to this version via a World Lit class at the University of North Carolina--Wilmington. It had such a deep effect on me that I re-read it several times and eventually read the five volume version numerous times. I would say that the five-volume translation has become probably my favorite of all-time, perhaps, next to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5129.Brave_New_World" title="Brave New World by Aldous Huxley" rel="nofollow noopener">Brave New World</a>. It has all the genius of the Romantic-era novels of manners, e.g. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1885.Pride_and_Prejudice" title="Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen" rel="nofollow noopener">Pride and Prejudice</a> set against a background of Taoism, Confucianism, Zen, and other types of Buddhism. It also touches on traditional Chinese medicine. I can't recommend this novel enough. The only reason I don't give this five stars is because you really must read the whole translation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3314332739583120573" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


